That the power of the Pale, which (to speak in general terms) was supposed to consist of the districts of Louth (or Uriel), Meam, Kildare, and Dublin, continued to decline, while the tributes paid to the Irish Chieftains increased, until a later period, or the year 1515, appears by the State Papers of the reign of Henry VIII. ‘⁴ Ther is,’' observe those docu- ments, “no Folke dayly subgett to the Kinges Lawes, but Half the Countye of Uryell, Half the Countye of Meam, Half the Countye of Dublyn‚ Half the Countye of Kyldare.” Of these, it is noted,—“ All the eomyn Peoplle of the said Halff Countyes, that obeyeth the Kinges
